eed a good trader or Ape Fund manager, those parts of your portfolio should increase on their own and â€˜running it backâ€™ after taking profit and moving it to your Liquid Spot Fund is pretty normal practice in crypto e.g. having an upper limit for money left on a CEX, and anything above that gets withdrawn.  Lastly, the sorely missing category is cash.  This is a really tough one because crypto traders like to go through extremes i.e. fully stabled up or fully deployed, and not much in between. So this more or less assumes your risk appetite is inclined towards the latter.  Generally, even in a fully deployed mindset, itâ€™s smart to keep at least some % of profits in cash for at least two reasons: first, to make some actual real world money + cover tax liabilities, and second, to be able to buy mispricings if thereâ€™s a severe deleveraging event.  Books have been written on portfolio theory and stuff, so naturplly this is very limited, imprecise, and incomplete.  It''s just something to get the brain juices flowing. ', '', False, NULL, False, 93337, 968, 125, 87, 629515, 6323.56, 6.98), (21631, '2024-02-09 08:27:38.000000', 1755871061248192962, 'CryptoDonAlt', 878219545785372673, 'twitter', '$BTC

