Pictured below is a cha price with another chart of aggregate open interest below. 

We can see that every time aggregate open interest hits about 10B, it tends to mark a local top and every time aggregate open interest hits about 6B, it tends to mark a major bottom.

So what is aggregate open interest and why is there this type of correlation?

A simple way to interpret aggregate open interest is that it is a measure of the total amount of leveraged positions currently open across all included exchanges. 

In other words- the higher aggregate open interest is, the more "frothy" the markets are as there is a larger amount open leveraged positions and these levered positions are all susceptible to liquidations if price moves against them. 

So at periods of time when the market gets too frothy and open interest is at higher levels (in this case around 10B), we often see some sort of violent move that causes a spike in volatility as the market seeks liquidity and leveraged players/positions are liquidated.

If/when these players are liquidated, their levered positions are forcibly CLOSED, and this causes aggregate open interest to drop. 

When most of the leverage has been flushed out of the system (in this case around 6B)- liquidations occur much less frequently which means volatility decreases and the price can then move back up (or down, depending on the trend) in a healthy manner.

So what can we do with this information and what does it tell us? 

First off, at current levels, leverage is not extremely high or extremely low- we have found ourselves at the middle of our range- so what I am looking for now is a move to either extremity. 

I have drawn two paths (green arrow and red arrow) that would likely take us to either extreme of our range.  

RED ARROW (preferred): This path would occur if we continued down to the mid to low 20k region from current levels- a further flush down to a logical retest level (25k) with some potential wicks below from cascading liquidations (wicks into 23-24k are fine) that would ideally flush out remaining levered players and bring us back down to a minimally leveraged (healthy) market environment from which we can continue on our way up to 30k+ and ultimately new all time highs.

GREEN ARROW (alternate): Alternatively, if we continue up from here without getting a proper flush to 25k levels and aggregate open interest continues to climb and approach 10B as we push back into the 30k''s- we have to remain cautious as it may simply be another fakeout to bait aggressive players in before a larger OI flush to sub 25k occurs.

Finally, is there a situation in which we DON''T need to revisit 25k and below and simply continue up and leave 25k and below untapped? 

Yes, but in order for this to happen we would need to move up WITHOUT OI rising too much which would indicate that the move up is primarily spot driven, which is healthy and sustainable. 

Overall I prefer the RED path as it would give us a visit to a logical support level and weekly bullish retest, while wiping out any excess froth from levered players which would allow us plenty of room to continue this healthy uptrend to new all time highs.

