We can start off by identifying key swing highs and swing lows- these are the levels marked off as "LOW" and "HIGH" in the chart below. We then look to see which of these levels has been broken during subsequent PA. We can see that our "LOW" has been broken (making a lower low) and our high remains unbroken (making current PA a lower high). At this stage, and at the highest level visible on the chart, we can conclude that we may be in a potential downtrend.

Now let''s look at what else we can see to determine if it''s likely that this downtrend continues or if it''s more likely that the trend is broken. To answer this question, let''s looks at logical draws on price (liquidity) and see if we can easily identify the path of least resistance for price to move towards:

On the chart below, I''ve marked off the two logical areas where we can expect resting liquidity with a RED X- the untapped/unbroken highs above us and the series of higher lows below us (near the bottom of the range).

I''ve also marked off some price zones in red and green (some call them gaps, or fair value gaps- same thing) to help identify regions in which PA moved inefficiently.

What does this means and why is it important? 

To simplify, imagine if you had a market with 100 buyers and sellers. 45 of them are interested in buying/selling at the range lows and 45 are interested in buying/selling at the range highs, but only 10 are interested in buying/selling in between. As price moves to the range highs and range lows we see lots of chop/trading as buyers and sellers duke it out to determine fair value. As price moves into the middle of the range, there aren''t many who are willing to transact at those prices, so the books are thin, volume is low, and price quickly moves through these zones with little resistance. This inefficient PA as we like to call it is often revisited and price often traverses through these regions quickly when it does because of the lack of buyers/sellers in these zones. This also means that these zones don''t do well as support/resistance. In other words- clusters of consolidation where lots of trading took place will often act as support/resistance whereas the inefficient moves between clusters of consolidation are often easily moved through with little resistance.

Now applying that idea to our chart above, we can see that the inefficiency left behind by price in green has been FILLED (meaning price has revisited it and "patched" the inefficiency) whereas the inefficiency below us in red remains unfilled. 

We can also see at the top left corner of the chart, that we have some more significant inefficiencies above our range altogether- so do we target the RED inefficiency below us or do we target the GREEN inefficiency outside/above our range? 

Let''s take a closer look at PA to help us answer this question:

If we look at where our reversal at our lows occurred we can see that smaller TF wicks below the range were bought up. These are signs of absorption (buyers stepping in to support price at these levels). If we look at where we are now, we can see the same- sellers stepping in to sell at these prices, the same way buyers stepped in to buy at the lows. This tells us, that while we do have some inefficiencies above our range, at this time, sellers are stepping in at the range highs and there is increased sell pressure at these levels which may prevent the range highs from being broken and the inefficiency above from being filled.

Because of increased sell pressure at these levels (evidenced by the wicks to the upside) the path of least resistance (at least in the immediate short term) may be down- and because of the large looming inefficiency below us it shouldn''t take much downwards PA for price to completely reverse this entire last move up and fill the inefficiency below us. 

Putting this all together, let''s take a look at what my expectations are here based on the logic shared above: 

With all this being said, it''s important to understand that there are no guarantees in markets and the above is a logical conclusion based on the data that we can see on the chart (which in and of itself encompasses all known market information at any given time) but by no means a guarantee. We CAN see something different play out. Some have suggested a move above the range highs as a range deviation before continuation down, others have suggested a move above the range highs to fill the large inefficiency in the low 20k''s- all of these are certainly viable possibilities- however- until the range highs (marked as HIGH) are breached, neither of these scenarios can come into play which is why my primary expectation is the one shared above. 

